<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12033b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12033b">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12033b"> 33(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Conrart breaks silence / to write a b&ecirc;tise</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Toutefois, il est bien certain qu&apos;elle parla de cette visite &agrave; la Cour et &agrave; la Ville. J&apos;en ai la preuve dans une pi&egrave;ce de vers que le fameux Conrart, c&eacute;l&egrave;bre par son silence, adressait &agrave; Mme de S&eacute;vign&eacute;. Chose singuli&egrave;re! La muse de Conrart est plut&ocirc;t bavarde; elle babille tout au long d&apos;une colonne de soixante-seize alexandrins. Vous les trouverez dans le manuscrit 5418 de la Biblioth&egrave;que de l&apos;Arsenal, &agrave; Paris, tome IX, fos 485-486. Conrart termine sa longue &eacute;pitre par cette affreuse tirade: <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <br> <font color="green">[It was in any case certain that she mentioned the visit both at the Court and in the City. I have proof in the form of a verse that the famous Conrart, famous by his silence, wrote to Madame de S&eacute;vign&eacute;. Strange case! Conrart&apos;s muse is rather talkative: she babbles in a long column of 76 alexandrines. You will find it in manuscript 5418 of the Library at the Arsenal in Paris, volume IX, folios 485-486. Conrart ends his long epistle with this awful tirade: [&hellip;]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 199</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
